[
  "div",
  {
    "className": "content-wrapper"
  },
  [
    "h1",
    {},
    "Interrogative Pronouns"
  ],
  [
    "p",
    {},
    "Interrogative pronouns are used to ask questions. In Greek, almost all interrogative pronouns carry an accent mark to distinguish them from their non-interrogative counterparts."
  ],
  [
    "div",
    {
      "className": "content-grid mt-8"
    },
    [
      "p",
      {},
      "ποιος, ποια, ποιο"
    ],
    [
      "h3",
      {},
      "Who / Which"
    ],
    [
      "p",
      {},
      "Used to ask about identity. It declines like an adjective."
    ],
    [
      "p",
      {},
      [
        [
          "strong",
          {},
          "Ποιος"
        ],
        " είναι στην πόρτα; ",
        [
          "strong",
          {},
          "Who"
        ],
        " is at the door?πόσος, πόση, πόσο"
      ]
    ],
    [
      "h3",
      {},
      "How much / many"
    ],
    [
      "p",
      {},
      "Used to ask about quantity."
    ],
    [
      "p",
      {},
      [
        [
          "strong",
          {},
          "Πόσο"
        ],
        " κάνει; ",
        [
          "strong",
          {},
          "How much"
        ],
        " does it cost?τι"
      ]
    ],
    [
      "h3",
      {},
      "What"
    ],
    [
      "p",
      {},
      "The universal \"what\". It is indeclinable (stays the same)."
    ],
    [
      "p",
      {},
      [
        [
          "strong",
          {},
          "Τι"
        ],
        " κάνεις; ",
        [
          "strong",
          {},
          "What"
        ],
        " are you doing?"
      ]
    ]
  ],
  [
    "div",
    {
      "className": "info-box mt-12 mb-12"
    },
    [
      "h3",
      {},
      "Accentuation Note"
    ],
    [
      "p",
      {},
      [
        "In Modern Greek, one of the few words that ",
        [
          "strong",
          {},
          "always"
        ],
        " keep their accent even when they are single-syllable are interrogative words (πώς, πού, τι can be an exception but usually keeps the context). The accent tells the reader \"this is a question\"."
      ]
    ]
  ]
]